diff:1668203093:1668043474:=47,65c47%0a%3c #foxbegin 221111-214453-859290#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Plural form of you in other Languages and the Association with the Formal %0a%3c -> - julia%0a%3c -> [-11.11.2022 - 13:44-]%0a%3c >>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a%3c (:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c {[foxdelrange button 221111-214453-859290 {$FullName} ]}%0a%3c (:if1end:)%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c It varies language to language, and in the case of English, dialect to dialect, whether the plural you has a separate word from the singular you, or is inferred from context. %0a%3c %0a%3c One interesting phenomenon to do with the plural you is also used as the formal you for some languages. For example, in French, you have the singular “tu”, and then the plural “vous” which is also the formal you, and in Telugu, you have the singular “nuuvu”, and the plural “meeru” which is also used for speaking to a person of higher status. Though it didn't help me gain clarity about how this pattern arose, I found this stack overflow discussion about it pretty interesting: https://linguistics.stackexchange.com/questions/2445/plural-you-in-different-language-families-connoting-respect%0a%3c %0a%3c In general, the wikipedia article on formality of pronouns/the T-V distinction, claims that the two main ways of denoting the formal you are addressing a single person using the second person plural pronoun, or using an entirely different pronoun. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T%25E2%2580%2593V_distinction). %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 221111-214453-859290#%0a---%0a> %0a
